{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503837"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:08:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.43,0.16,0.2,0.15,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113871"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2088"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95891"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"398"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47271"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113871"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents with a three month history of episodic colicky abdominal pain. When it occurs the pain is generalised and is accompanied with nausea and abdominal bloating. These episodes may last several hours before resolving spontaneously. He has lost 5 kg in weight over the last six months, but has no other current medical problems. His medical history is unremarkable and he does not use any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure is 128/82 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is soft and there are no identifiable masses on palpation and bowel sounds are normal. A CT scan is performed and two representative slices are shown (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intussusception","Crohn disease","Adhesion-obstruction","Diverticulitis","Irritable bowel syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s symptoms are rather vague and could be explained by several of the options provided. However, the CT scan shows the characteristic features on an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintussusception.\u003C/strong\u003E It has a clear \u0027target\u0027 sign on the axial view (Image 1) and on the coronal view a long length intussusception with the lipoma (round hypodense point near midline) as well as a long length of fatty mesentry being sucked into the intussuscipiens (Image 2). There are no other abnormal findings on the CT. Intussusception occurs when a part of the intestine invaginates into the adjacent intestinal segment. Even though intussusception is more common in children, the adult population may be affected as well. Adult intussusception can have a number of different causes, these varying with the site. One of the most common causes of intussusception in adult is malignancy, this being responsible for about 30% of the cases originating in the small bowel. In this case the cause is a lipoma. This has been causing recurrent episodes of small bowel obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntestinal \u003Cstrong\u003Eobstruction due to adhesions \u003C/strong\u003Eusually has an acute presentation. In this case the physical examination findings of a soft, non-distended abdomen with normal bowel sounds further decreases the likelihood of adhesion-obstruction. In the absence of any previous abdominal surgery adhesion formation is unlikely, but not impossible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrohn disease\u003C/strong\u003E may cause chronic abdominal pain and unintentional weight loss, however the lack of diarrhoea and haematochezia make this diagnosis less likely. Furthermore, there is clear evidence on the CT-scan an intussusception with the lead point shown. \u003Cstrong\u003EIrritable bowel syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely to cause 5kg weight loss within three months. History of unintentional weight loss is a \u0027red flag\u0027 and an indication for further assessment to rule out other pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon clinical presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticulitis \u003C/strong\u003Einclude bloody stools and lower abdominal pain accompanied with inflammatory symptoms such as fever. That is not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intussusception is an uncommon, but well recognised cause of intestinal obstruction."],"references":["Panzera F, Di Venere B, Rizzi M, Biscaglia A, Pratic\u00f2 CA, Nasti G, Mardighian A, Nunes TF, Inchingolo R. Bowel intussusception in adult: prevalence, diagnostic tools and therapy. World Journal of Methodology. 2021 May 20;11(3):81."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95891"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22113"},{"type":"media","id":"22114"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22115"},{"type":"media","id":"22116"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22113"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/